{"title_page": "Ch\u00e9rif Ousmane Sarr", "text_new": "{{short description|French-Senegalese footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name= Ousmane Sarr\n| fullname = Ch\u00e9rif Ousmane Sarr\n| image = Ousmane Sarr 20120329.jpg\n| image_size = 220\n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1986|8|2}}\n| birth_place = [[Fatick]], Senegal\n| height = 1.87 m\n| currentclub = [[USM Saran|Saran]]\n| clubnumber = \n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = CFSFA Dakar\n| youthyears2 = 2003\u20132004\n| youthclubs2 = [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]\n| years1 = 2004\u20132006\n| clubs1 = [[AS Saint-\u00c9tienne|Saint-\u00c9tienne B]]\n| caps1 = 45\n| goals1 = 4\n| years2 = 2006\u20132007\n| clubs2 = [[Grenoble Foot 38|Grenoble]]\n| caps2 = 27\n| goals2 = 2\n| years3 = 2007\u20132008\n| clubs3 = [[Troyes AC|Troyes]]\n| caps3 = 30\n| goals3 = 2\n| years4 = 2010\u20132011\n| clubs4 = [[Randers FC]]\n| caps4 = 21\n| goals4 = 4\n| years5 = 2012\u20132013\n| clubs5 = [[Viborg FF|Viborg]]\n| caps5 = 27\n| goals5 = 7\n| years6 = 2019\u2013\n| clubs6 = [[USM Saran|Saran]]\n| caps6 = 5\n| goals6 = 1\n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1 = \n| nationalcaps1 = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| pcupdate = 01:31, 3 November 2019 (UTC)\n| ntupdate =\n}}\n\n'''Ch\u00e9rif Ousmane Sarr''' (born 2 August 1986) is a [[association football|football]] [[midfielder]] who plays for French lower-league club [[USM Saran]].\n\n==Career==\nSarr was born in [[Fatick]], Senegal. He signed for then [[Ligue 2]] side [[Troyes AC]] in the summer of 2007 from [[Grenoble Foot 38]]. He [[Rescission (contract law)|rescinded]] the contract on 29 September 2009 despite his deal lasting until June 2011.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071012231856/http://www.estac.fr/breves9.htm  Ousmane Sarr quitte l'Estac]</ref>\n\nHe trained with the Danish champions [[F.C. Copenhagen]] in July 2010 and other Danish clubs, primarily [[Randers FC]], showed interest in him. He signed a one-year contract with Randers FC on 3 August 2010.<ref>[http://www.randersfc.dk/index.php?afd=1&side=4550 Ousmane Sarr p\u00e5 et-\u00e5rig kontrakt]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Lequipe|20912}}\n* {{Soccerway|ousmane-sarr/1323}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sarr, Ousmane}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Fatick Region]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Senegalese footballers]]\n[[Category:Senegalese expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Serer sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Danish Superliga players]]\n[[Category:Danish 1st Division players]]\n[[Category:Ligue 2 players]]\n[[Category:Championnat National 3 players]]\n[[Category:Grenoble Foot 38 players]]\n[[Category:Troyes AC players]]\n[[Category:Randers FC players]]\n[[Category:Viborg FF players]]\n[[Category:Senegalese expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Senegalese expatriate sportspeople in France]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in France]]\n[[Category:Senegalese expatriate sportspeople in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Denmark]]\n\n{{Senegal-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French-Senegalese footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name= Ousmane Sarr\n| fullname = Ch\u00e9rif Ousmane Sarr\n| image = Ousmane Sarr 20120329.jpg\n| image_size = 220\n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1986|8|2}}\n| birth_place = [[Fatick]], Senegal\n| height = {{height|m=1.87}}\n| currentclub = [[USM Saran|Saran]]\n| clubnumber = \n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = CFSFA Dakar \n| youthyears2 = 2003\u20132004\n| youthclubs2 = [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]\n| years1 = 2004\u20132006 \n| years2 = 2006\u20132007 \n| years3 = 2007\u20132008 \n| years4 = 2010\u20132011\n| years5 = 2012\u20132013\n| years6 = 2019\u2013\n| clubs1 = [[AS Saint-\u00c9tienne|Saint-\u00c9tienne B]] \n| clubs2 = [[Grenoble Foot 38|Grenoble]] \n| clubs3 = [[Troyes AC|Troyes]] \n| clubs4 = [[Randers FC]]\n| clubs5 = [[Viborg FF|Viborg]]\n| clubs6 = [[USM Saran|Saran]]\n| caps1 = 45  \n| caps2 = 27  \n| caps3 = 30  \n| caps4 = 21  \n| caps5 = 27\n| caps6 = 5\n| goals1 = 4  \n| goals2 = 2  \n| goals3 = 2  \n| goals4 = 4 \n| goals5 = 7\n| goals6 = 1\n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1 = \n| nationalcaps1 = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| pcupdate = 01:31, 3 November 2019 (UTC)\n| ntupdate =\n}}\n\n'''Ch\u00e9rif Ousmane Sarr''' (born 2 August 1986) is a [[association football|football]] [[midfielder]] who plays for French club [[USM Saran]].\n\n==Career==\nSarr was born in [[Fatick]], Senegal. He signed for then [[Ligue 2]] side [[Troyes AC]] in the summer of 2007 from [[Grenoble Foot 38]]. He [[Rescission (contract law)|rescinded]] the contract on 29 September 2009 despite his deal lasting until June 2011.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071012231856/http://www.estac.fr/breves9.htm  Ousmane Sarr quitte l'Estac]</ref>\n\nHe trained with the Danish champions [[F.C. Copenhagen]] in July 2010 and other Danish clubs, primarily [[Randers FC]], showed interest in him. He signed a one-year contract with Randers FC on 3 August 2010.<ref>[http://www.randersfc.dk/index.php?afd=1&side=4550 Ousmane Sarr p\u00e5 et-\u00e5rig kontrakt]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Lequipe|20912}}\n* {{Soccerway|ousmane-sarr/1323}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sarr, Ousmane}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Fatick Region]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Senegalese footballers]]\n[[Category:Senegalese expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Serer sportspeople]]\n[[Category:Danish Superliga players]]\n[[Category:Danish 1st Division players]]\n[[Category:Ligue 2 players]]\n[[Category:Championnat National 3 players]]\n[[Category:Grenoble Foot 38 players]]\n[[Category:Troyes AC players]]\n[[Category:Randers FC players]]\n[[Category:Viborg FF players]]\n[[Category:Senegalese expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Senegalese expatriate sportspeople in France]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in France]]\n[[Category:Senegalese expatriate sportspeople in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Denmark]]\n\n{{Senegal-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "Clean up infobox code.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ch%C3%A9rif_Ousmane_Sarr"}
{"title_page": "Hurricane (clipper)", "text_new": "{{short description|Extreme clipper}} \n{|{{Infobox ship begin <!-- full code -->\n|infobox caption= <!-- keywords: yes, nodab; or caption text -->\n|display title= <!-- keywords: none, ital; or article title with markup -->\n}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image= File:Hurricane (clipper ship).jpg \n|Ship image size=\n|Ship caption= ''Hurricane'' in the [[English Channel]]; detail of a [[lithograph]] after a painting by [[Stephen Dadd Skillet]] \n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=\n|Ship flag=\n|Ship name= '''''Hurricane''''' \n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship owner= C. W. & A. Thomas \n|Ship operator=\n|Ship registry= *New York (1851&ndash;60) \n*[[Singapore]] (after 1860) \n|Ship route=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship awarded=\n|Ship builder= [[Isaac C. Smith]] ([[Hoboken, New Jersey]]) \n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched= 25 Oct 1851 \n|Ship sponsor=\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship recommissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship maiden voyage= 17 Dec 1851 \n|Ship in service= 1851&ndash;57; 1859&ndash;76? \n|Ship out of service= 1857&ndash;58 \n|Ship renamed= ''Shaw-Allum'' (ca. 1860) \n|Ship reclassified=\n|Ship refit=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship homeport=\n|Ship identification=\n|Ship motto=\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship honors=\n|Ship captured=\n|Ship fate= Unknown; disappears from shipping registers after 1876 \n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes= Reputedly the most extreme clipper ever built<p>Made several record port-to-port or point-to-point passages \n|Ship badge=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=\n|Ship type= [[Extreme clipper]] \n|Ship tonnage= \n|Ship displacement=\n|Ship tons burthen= 1608 \n|Ship length= *{{convert|230|ft|abbr=on}} (oa) \n*{{convert|215|ft|abbr=on}} (deck) \n*{{convert|206|ft|abbr=on}} ([[keel]]) \n|Ship beam= {{convert|40|ft|abbr=on}} \n|Ship height=\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship draft= {{convert|20|ft|abbr=on}} \n|Ship depth=\n|Ship hold depth= {{convert|22|ft|abbr=on}} \n|Ship decks= Two \n|Ship deck clearance=\n|Ship ramps=\n|Ship ice class=\n|Ship power=\n|Ship propulsion=\n|Ship sail plan= [[Ship-rigged]] \n|Ship speed= {{convert|18|knot|mph km/h|lk=on}} in ideal conditions; typical speed {{convert|7-10|kn}} \n|Ship range=\n|Ship endurance=\n|Ship test depth=\n|Ship boats=\n|Ship capacity=\n|Ship troops=\n|Ship complement=\n|Ship crew=\n|Ship time to activate=\n|Ship sensors=\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=\n|Ship armour=\n|Ship armor=\n|Ship aircraft=\n|Ship aircraft facilities=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n'''''Hurricane''''' was a large [[extreme clipper]] of 1608 [[tons burthen]] built in [[Hoboken, New Jersey]] in 1851. Reputedly the most extreme clipper ever built, ''Hurricane'' proved a very fast vessel, reportedly capable of speeds of up to {{convert|18|kn|mph km/h}} in ideal conditions, and establishing a number of record or record-equalling passages in the early years of her career. \n\n''Hurricane'' made a total of four [[New York City|New York]]-to-[[San Francisco]] voyages while under the American flag, the fastest of which was an outstanding 100-day passage in 1854. After arriving at San Francisco, the ship would usually continue on to China or [[Hong Kong]] before returning via San Francisco to New York. She also made several voyages between England and India during this period, including a record 1855 passage that stood for many years. \n\nDue partly to [[Panic of 1857|an economic depression]] in the United States, ''Hurricane'' was laid up for about a year at New York in 1857&ndash;58. In late 1858, she sailed via San Francisco for [[Singapore]], where in 1860 she was sold to British interests. Renamed ''Shaw-Allum'', little is known about her subsequent career. Her last entry in shipping registers was in 1876. \n\n== Construction and design ==\n\n''Hurricane'', an extreme clipper, was built in Hoboken, New Jersey, in 1851 by [[Isaac C. Smith]].<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277/><ref name=fairburn_p2128>Fairburn 1945&ndash;55. '''III'''. p. [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015021129070?urlappend=%3Bseq=560 2128].</ref> The ship was originally referred to in press reports as ''Yankee Doodle'',<ref name=nyherald_14jun1851>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Marine Affairs |url= https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030313/1851-06-14/ed-1/seq-2/ |work= The New York Herald |date= 1851-06-14 |page= 2 |access-date= }}</ref> but this name was dropped while the vessel was still under construction. ''Hurricane'' was the first clipper built by Smith, who had \"no previous experiences in building fast sizeable ships\";<ref name=fairburn_p2128/> she was also by far the largest ship to come from Smith{{'}}s Hoboken shipyard.{{efn|See the shipbuilding record section in the [[Isaac C. Smith]] article.}} Her owners, C. W. & A. Thomas,{{efn|The firm is misnamed C. W. & '''H'''. Thomas in ''American Lloyds'', an error consequently repeated by some later sources.}} a firm involved mainly in the importation of French [[textile]]s to the United States, are not known to have owned any other notable clippers.<ref name=fairburn_p2128/>\n\n''Hurricane'' was built of [[live oak]], with [[white oak]] [[keel]], [[kelson]] and frame and \"live oak and [[Robinia|locust]] top\";<ref name=nytimes_11nov1851>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= New Clipper Ship 'Hurricane' |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/18157552/clipper_hurricane_launch_1851/ |work= The New York Times |date= 1851-11-11 |page= 1 }}</ref> her timbers were \"thoroughly salted on the stocks.\"<ref name=nytimes_11nov1851/> ''Hurricane''{{'}}s fastenings were of copper and iron, square bolted throughout, and she was said to be an exceptionally heavily timbered and strongly built vessel.<ref name=nytimes_11nov1851/> She had an overall length of {{convert|230|ft}}, {{convert|215|ft}} on deck and {{convert|206|ft}} keel, with a [[beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|40|ft}}, [[hold (ship)|hold]] depth of {{convert|22|ft}} and [[draft (hull)|draft]] of {{convert|20|ft}}.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277/><ref name=nytimes_11nov1851/><ref name=fairburn_p2129/> She had two decks, and was fitted with passenger accommodations in addition to her cargo capacity. Her registered tonnage was 1608 [[tons burthen]].<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277/><ref name=fairburn_p2128/><ref name=nytimes_11nov1851/> \n\nAccording to some authorities, ''Hurricane'' was \"the sharpest sailing ship ever constructed by any builder\"<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277/><ref name=nytimes_11nov1851/><ref name=fairburn_p2129>Fairburn 1945&ndash;55. '''III'''. p. [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015021129070?urlappend=%3Bseq=561 2129].</ref>&mdash;that is, the most extreme clipper<ref name=knoblock2014_p37>Knoblock 2014. p. 37.</ref>&mdash;though her model fore and aft is nonetheless said to have avoided [[concave]] lines.<ref name=nytimes_11nov1851/> She had a deadrise of {{convert|40|in|cm}}<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277/> typical of the early extreme clippers. It was said that no other vessel had lines below water \"sweeter than those of the ''Hurricane'', for, in her, resistance to driving through water was reduced to a minimum.\"<ref name=fairburn_p2129/> The disadvantage of such sharp lines was a corresponding reduction in cargo capacity, which ran the risk of making the extreme clippers unprofitable during periods of low freight rates.<ref name=fairburn_pp2128-29>Fairburn 1945&ndash;55. '''III'''. pp. [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015021129070?urlappend=%3Bseq=560 2128&ndash;29].</ref> At the time of ''Hurricane''{{'}}s debut, however, this was not a concern as rates were still at unprecedented highs due to the [[California Gold Rush]], then in full swing.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277>Howe and Matthews 1926. '''I'''. p. [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015020225044?urlappend=%3Bseq=347 277].</ref>\n\n''Hurricane'' had a \"graceful\" rising [[Bow (ship)|bow]] and rounded [[stern]], with a heavy brass rail running around the [[poop deck]].<ref name=nytimes_11nov1851/> The bow was decorated with a \"very handsome\" eagle{{'}}s head, which had a ribbon flowing from its mouth upon which was inscribed the ship{{'}}s name in gilt letters, the whole creating \"a very novel appearance.\"<ref name=nytimes_11nov1851/>{{efn|Howe and Matthews state that the eagle{{'}}s head and ribbon decorations were located on the ship{{'}}s stern rather than bow,<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277/> in contradiction of contemporaneous newspaper accounts.}} ''Hurricane'' was loftily sparred and fitted with rolling topsails, with her name emblazoned across the lower part of the foretopsail in large black lettering<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277/> \"that could be read much further than any signals and looked very smart and shipshape.\"<ref name=clark1910_p163/> Overall, she was described as a \"truly beautiful ship\".<ref name=nytimes_11nov1851/> \n\n=== Launch ===\n\n''Hurricane'' was launched with all her standing [[spar (sailing)|spars]]<ref name=nytimes_11nov1851/> on the morning of 25 October 1851,<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277/> witnessed by an \"immense concourse\" of spectators. After the launch, the vessel \"remained afloat several days with nearly all her [[yard (sailing)|yards]] aloft, without a pound of [[ballast]] in her\", a tribute to her stability.<ref name=nytimes_11nov1851/>\n\n''Hurricane''{{'}}s launch was widely reported across the country, with some seeing the event not merely as the launch of an exceptional ship, but as a symbol of the growing confidence of the young Republic. A reporter from a [[Washington, D.C.]], periodical, after noting how the vessel \"sparred enormously, looms up prodigiously ... [and] overtops and belittles everything afloat lying near\"<ref name=therepublic_5nov1851>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= New York Correspondence |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/18582739/hurricane_clipper_grandeur/ |work= The Republic |location= Washington, D.C. |date= 1851-11-05 |page= 2}}</ref> was given to further reflect that \"The tendency in every thing with us is toward magnificence of dimensions ... the day of cheap things is past altogether. Grandeur, speed and magnificence are the ruling ideas in the American mind.\"<ref name=therepublic_5nov1851/> Another journalist from [[North Carolina]] was sufficiently moved by news of the launch to declare: \"We are a great people and [[Nicknames of New York City|Gotham]] is magnificent.\"<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Big Ships |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19312121/hurricane_1851_clipper_launch_means_a/ |work= Weekly Commercial |location= Wilmington, NC |date= 1851-11-14 |page= 2 }}</ref> Others confined their admiration to the ship itself. A reporter writing some weeks after the launch described the ship \"with all her sails and colors flying\" as \"one of the most cheering nautical sights ever shown in this region\".<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Kossuth in New York |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19312167/hurricane_1851_clipper_a_cheering/ |work= The Raleigh Register |location= Raleigh, NC |date= 1851-12-13 |page= 2 }}</ref>\n\n=== Command ===\n\n''Hurricane''{{'}}s first master, who would command the vessel for the first six years of her service, was Captain Samuel Very Jr., son of John Crowninshield Very, a [[Salem, Massachusetts|Salem]] mariner,<ref name=fairburn_p2128/> and father of future [[United States Navy]] [[Rear Admiral]] Samuel W. Very.<ref name=clark1910_p163>Clark 1910. p. [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/hvd.hntl1d?urlappend=%3Bseq=215 163].</ref> Captain Very Jr. would prove to be \"a capable master and good navigator\",<ref name=fairburn_p2128/> under whose command ''Hurricane'' would set or equal a number of point-to-point or port-to-port records.{{efn|See service history section below.}}\n\n== Service history ==\n=== Very captaincy, 1851&ndash;57 === \n[[ File:Hurricane (1851 clipper) maiden voyage advertisement.jpg | thumb | Advertisement for ''Hurricane''{{'}}s maiden voyage ]] \nPrior to ''Hurricane''{{'}}s launch, a voyage to [[China]] via [[San Francisco]], [[California]], had already been organized for the vessel, but some weeks were to pass after launch before the ship was ready to sail. ''Hurricane'' eventually departed New York for San Francisco on her maiden voyage on 17 December 1851, with Captain Samuel Very Jr. in command.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277/>\n\nSixteen days out from New York, ''Hurricane''{{'}}s fore and main topmasts and mizzen topgallant mast were lost in a [[white squall]], but despite the mishap, the ship crossed the equator in good time and arrived at [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]], on 28 January 1852, where she put in for repairs.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277/><ref name=fairburn_pp2129-30>Fairburn 1945&ndash;55. '''III'''. pp. [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015021129070?urlappend=%3Bseq=561 2129&ndash;2130].</ref> These were effected in the space of 12 days<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277/>&mdash;then considered a remarkably short time for this port<ref name=fairburn_p2130>Fairburn 1945&ndash;55. '''III'''. p. [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015021129070?urlappend=%3Bseq=562 2130].</ref>&mdash;and the ship resumed her journey 9 February,<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277/><ref name=fairburn_p2130/> reaching the [[Pacific Ocean]] 24 days later and enjoying a \"fine run\"<ref name=howe&matthews_I_pp277-78>Howe and Matthews 1926. '''I'''. pp. [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015020225044?urlappend=%3Bseq=347 277&ndash;78].</ref> of 18 days to the equator, thereafter completing the final leg to San Francisco in 24 days, where she arrrived 15 April.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_pp277-78/> ''Hurricane''{{'}}s time on her first New York&ndash;to&ndash;San Francisco voyage was 120 days overall including the 12-day stopover at Rio, her net sailing days thus totalling just 108, while her run of 66 days from Rio to San Francisco<ref name=fairburn_p2130/> has been described as \"only once beaten and only twice equalled\"<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p278/> in the history of merchant sail.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p278>Howe and Matthews 1926. '''I'''. p. [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015020225044?urlappend=%3Bseq=348 278].</ref> ''Hurricane'' is also said to have travelled 400 nautical miles in a single day on the passage from Rio, at times reaching speeds of up to 18 knots,<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277/><ref name=fairburn_p2130/> and while this claim has been queried, according to [[naval architect]] [[William Armstrong Fairburn|William Fairburn]] the vessel was \"fully capable\"<ref name=fairburn_p2130/> of achieving such speeds in the right conditions.<ref name=fairburn_p2130/> \n\nAfter making port at San Francisco, ''Hurricane'' continued on her scheduled trip to China, returning to San Francisco from [[Pazhou|Whampoa]] 20 October after a 43-day transpacific crossing.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p278/> The ship then made a second transpacific crossing, this time to [[Hong Kong]], in a time of 44 days.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p278/> Loading again at Whampoa, the vessel cleared port 12 February 1853 for her home port of New York, arriving at her destination 18 May after a passage of 94 1/2 days.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p278/>\n\n''Hurricane'' departed on her second New York&ndash;to&ndash;San Francisco voyage on 9 August 1853, but on this trip was beset by much calm weather as well as losing her [[jibboom]] and foretopgallant mast in the vicinity of [[Cape Horn]], before arriving at San Francisco after a 123-day passage.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p278/> In spite of the adverse conditions encountered, ''Hurricane''{{'}}s run of 25 days from [[Sandy Hook]] to the equator on the outset of this voyage is said to have \"never been bettered and seldom equalled for August departures.\"<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p278/> ''Hurricane'' then returned to New York in ballast, clearing San Francisco 31 December and arriving at her destination in early April after a passage of 96 days.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p278/>\n[[ File:Flyingcloudclipper2.jpg | thumb | left | The clipper [[Flying Cloud (clipper)|''Flying Cloud'']]]] \n''Hurricane''{{'}}s third and fastest New York&ndash;to&ndash;San Francisco voyage began on 26 May 1854. After just 85 days in transit, the ship was only 1,040 miles from San Francisco and within striking distance of [[Flying Cloud (clipper)|''Flying Cloud'']]{{'}}s all-time record passage of 89 days, but at this point was beset by light winds and calms,<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p278/> taking another two weeks to cover the remaining distance and eventually logging a nonetheless outstanding passage of 100 days (99 days 16 hours pilot to pilot).<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p279>Howe and Matthews 1926. '''I'''. p. [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015020225044?urlappend=%3Bseq=349 279].</ref><ref name=fairburn_p2130/> Captain Very was particularly proud of his ship{{'}}s performance through the challenging region of [[the tropics]] on this voyage, noting that the vessel averaged more than {{convert|8|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} through both the Atlantic and Pacific legs, and recording in his log the conviction that \"these two portions of our passage have rarely, if ever, been equalled\"<ref name=fairburn_p2130/>&mdash;both legs later verified by Cutler as all-time records.<ref name=cutler1952_p109>Cutler 1952. p. 109.</ref> Fairburn has additionally noted ''Hurricane''{{'}}s \"unusually uniform\"<ref name=fairburn_p2131>Fairburn 1945&ndash;55. '''III'''. p. [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015021129070?urlappend=%3Bseq=563 2131].</ref> speeds under varying conditions on this passage,<ref name=fairburn_p2131/> and argued that with a little more good fortune, the vessel could well have set considerably faster times throughout her career.<ref name=fairburn_p2129/>\n\nAfter arriving at San Francisco, ''Hurricane'' made a 40-day passage to Hong Kong, departing 21 September and arriving 1 November, before continuing on to [[Calcutta]], [[India]], on a leg which included a very fast passage of 6 1/2 days from Hong Kong to [[Singapore]] at an average speed of just under {{convert|10|kn|mph km/h}}.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p279/><ref name=fairburn_p2132>Fairburn 1945&ndash;55. '''III'''. p. [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015021129070?urlappend=%3Bseq=564 2132].</ref> Clearing Calcutta 3 February 1855, the ship made a 100-day passage around the [[Cape of Good Hope]] to [[London]], [[England]].<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p279/> From London, the vessel returned to Calcutta, on this occasion making the run from [[The Needles]] to the mouth of the [[Hooghly River]] in 82 1/4 days,<ref name=fairburn_p2132/> setting a record \"not beaten or equalled for many years thereafter.\"<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p279/> Leaving Calcutta 10 January 1856, the ship returned to [[Falmouth, Cornwall|Falmouth]], England, in the fast time of 83 days (79 sailing days)<ref name=fairburn_p2132/> before departing from London for Hong Kong, where she arrived 5 October 1856.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p279/> \n\nAfter almost four months at Hong Kong, ''Hurricane'' sailed for San Francisco 20 January 1857, arriving 13 March.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p279/> At this point, an unsuccessful attempt was made to sell the vessel. ''Hurricane'' eventually sailed from San Francisco 16 June for New York, arriving 28 September 1857 after a 104-day passage.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p279/> This was to be the last voyage of ''Hurricane'' under the command of Captain Very,<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277/><ref name=fairburn_p2128/> whose family returned to New York with him on this passage.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Postscript |url= http://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2010/New%20York%20NY%20Evening%20Post/New%20York%20NY%20Evening%20Post%201857%20Grayscale/New%20York%20NY%20Evening%20Post%201857%20Grayscale%20-%200932.pdf |work= The Evening Post |location= New York |date= 1857-09-29 |page= 3}}</ref>\n\n=== Later history ===\n[[ File:Hurricane (1851 clipper) last voyage to San Francisco advert.jpg | thumb | Advertisement for ''Hurricane''{{'}}s last New York to San Francisco voyage, 1858 ]] \nAfter returning to New York in September 1857, ''Hurricane'' was laid up with no work until the end of 1858 due to low freight rates caused in part by [[Panic of 1857|an economic depression]] in the United States.<ref name=fairburn_p2128/><ref name=howe&matthews_I_p279/> While other vessels could continue to operate profitably in such conditions, extreme clippers like ''Hurricane'', with their high operating costs and relatively light tonnages, could not.<ref name=fairburn_p2128/><ref name=howe&matthews_I_p279/> Toward the end of 1858, ''Hurricane'' was again placed in commission&mdash;reportedly in hopes of finding a buyer&mdash;and on 8 January 1859, departed for the fourth and final time for San Francisco, Captain Ichabod Sherman in command.<ref name=fairburn_p2128/><ref name=howe&matthews_I_p279/><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Ocean Steamers, &c. |url= http://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%206/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201858%20Oct%20-%20Dec%20Grayscale/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201858%20Oct%20-%20Dec%20Grayscale%20-%200519.pdf |work= New-York Daily Tribune |date= 1858-12-15 |page= 3 }}</ref> On this voyage, ''Hurricane'' reportedly experienced much adverse weather, arriving at San Francisco 30 May after an unexceptional 143-day passage.<ref name=fairburn_p2128/><ref name=howe&matthews_I_p280>Howe and Matthews 1926. '''I'''. p. [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015020225044?urlappend=%3Bseq=350 280].</ref>\n\nFrom San Francisco, ''Hurricane'' sailed for Singapore 3 September, arriving 7 November.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p280/> There, she was sold in 1860 for US$30,000 ({{inflation|US|30,000|1859|fmt=eq|cursign=US$}}) and went under the [[United Kingdom|British]] flag.<ref name=fairburn_p2128/><ref name=howe&matthews_I_p280/> Renamed ''Shaw-Allum'',<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p280/> little is known about the vessel{{'}}s subsequent career.<ref name=fairburn_p2128/> Her last known mention in shipping registers was in 1876.<ref name=fairburn_p2128/><ref name=howe&matthews_I_p280/>\n\n== Footnotes == \n{{notelist}}\n\n== References == \n{{Reflist|30em}} \n=== Bibliography ===\n\n* {{cite book |last= Clark |first= Arthur Hamilton |date= 1910 |title= The Clipper Ship Era: An Epitome of Famous American and British Clipper Ships, Their Owners, Builders, Commanders, and Crews 1843&ndash;1869 |location= New York |publisher= G. P. Putnam{{'}}s Sons |page= [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/hvd.hntl1d?urlappend=%3Bseq=215 163] }} \n* {{cite book |last= Fairburn |first= William Armstrong |date= 1945\u201355 |title= Merchant Sail |volume= III |location= Center Lovell, Maine |publisher= Fairburn Marine Educational Foundation, Inc. |pages= [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015021129070?urlappend=%3Bseq=560 2128\u201332] |author-link= }} \n* {{cite book |last= Howe |first= Octavius T. |last2= Matthews |first2= Frederick C. |date= 1926 |title= American Clipper Ships 1833\u20131858 |volume= I |location= Salem, Massachusetts |publisher= Marine Research Society |pages= [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015020225044?urlappend=%3Bseq=347 277\u201380] }}\n* {{cite book |last= Knoblock |first= Glenn A. |author-link= |date= 2014 |title= The American Clipper Ship, 1845\u20141920 |location= Jefferson, NC |publisher= McFarland & Company |page= 37 |isbn= 9780786471126 }} \n[[Category:1851 ships]] \n[[Category:Ships built by Isaac C. Smith| ]] \n[[Category:Clipper ships built in New Jersey| ]] \n[[Category:Ships built in Hoboken, New Jersey| ]] \n[[Category:Extreme clippers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Extreme clipper}} \n{|{{Infobox ship begin <!-- full code -->\n|infobox caption= <!-- keywords: yes, nodab; or caption text -->\n|display title= <!-- keywords: none, ital; or article title with markup -->\n}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image= File:Hurricane (clipper ship).jpg \n|Ship image size=\n|Ship caption= ''Hurricane'' in the [[English Channel]]; detail of a [[lithograph]] after a painting by [[Stephen Dadd Skillet]] \n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=\n|Ship flag=\n|Ship name= '''''Hurricane''''' \n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship owner= C. W. & A. Thomas \n|Ship operator=\n|Ship registry= *New York (1851&ndash;60) \n*[[Singapore]] (after 1860) \n|Ship route=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship awarded=\n|Ship builder= [[Isaac C. Smith]] ([[Hoboken, New Jersey]]) \n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched= 25 Oct 1851 \n|Ship sponsor=\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship recommissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship maiden voyage= 17 Dec 1851 \n|Ship in service= 1851&ndash;57; 1859&ndash;76? \n|Ship out of service= 1857&ndash;58 \n|Ship renamed= ''Shaw-Allum'' (ca. 1860) \n|Ship reclassified=\n|Ship refit=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship homeport=\n|Ship identification=\n|Ship motto=\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship honors=\n|Ship captured=\n|Ship fate= Unknown; disappears from shipping registers after 1876 \n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes= Reputedly the most extreme clipper ever built<p>Made several record port-to-port or point-to-point passages \n|Ship badge=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=\n|Ship type= [[Extreme clipper]] \n|Ship tonnage= \n|Ship displacement=\n|Ship tons burthen= 1608 \n|Ship length= *{{convert|230|ft|abbr=on}} (oa) \n*{{convert|215|ft|abbr=on}} (deck) \n*{{convert|206|ft|abbr=on}} ([[keel]]) \n|Ship beam= {{convert|40|ft|abbr=on}} \n|Ship height=\n|Ship draught=\n|Ship draft= {{convert|20|ft|abbr=on}} \n|Ship depth=\n|Ship hold depth= {{convert|22|ft|abbr=on}} \n|Ship decks= Two \n|Ship deck clearance=\n|Ship ramps=\n|Ship ice class=\n|Ship power=\n|Ship propulsion=\n|Ship sail plan= [[Ship-rigged]] \n|Ship speed= {{convert|18|knot|mph km/h|lk=on}} in ideal conditions; typical speed {{convert|7-10|kn}} \n|Ship range=\n|Ship endurance=\n|Ship test depth=\n|Ship boats=\n|Ship capacity=\n|Ship troops=\n|Ship complement=\n|Ship crew=\n|Ship time to activate=\n|Ship sensors=\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=\n|Ship armour=\n|Ship armor=\n|Ship aircraft=\n|Ship aircraft facilities=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n'''''Hurricane''''' was a large [[extreme clipper]] of 1608 [[tons burthen]] built in [[Hoboken, New Jersey]] in 1851. Reputedly the most extreme clipper ever built, ''Hurricane'' proved a very fast vessel, reportedly capable of speeds of up to {{convert|18|kn|mph km/h}} in ideal conditions, and establishing a number of record or record-equalling passages in the early years of her career. \n\n''Hurricane'' made a total of four [[New York City|New York]]-to-[[San Francisco]] voyages while under the American flag, the fastest of which was an outstanding 100-day passage in 1854. After arriving at San Francisco, the ship would usually continue on to China or [[Hong Kong]] before returning via San Francisco to New York. She also made several voyages between England and India during this period, including a record 1855 passage that stood for many years. \n\nDue partly to [[Panic of 1857|an economic depression]] in the United States, ''Hurricane'' was laid up for about a year at New York in 1857&ndash;58. In late 1858, she sailed via San Francisco for [[Singapore]], where in 1860 she was sold to British interests. Renamed ''Shaw-Allum'', little is known about her subsequent career. Her last entry in shipping registers was in 1876. \n\n== Construction and design ==\n\n''Hurricane'', an extreme clipper, was built in Hoboken, New Jersey, in 1851 by [[Isaac C. Smith]].<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277/><ref name=fairburn_p2128>Fairburn 1945&ndash;55. '''III'''. p. [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015021129070?urlappend=%3Bseq=560 2128].</ref> The ship was originally referred to in press reports as ''Yankee Doodle'',<ref name=nyherald_14jun1851>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Marine Affairs |url= https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030313/1851-06-14/ed-1/seq-2/ |work= The New York Herald |date= 1851-06-14 |page= 2 |access-date= }}</ref> but this name was dropped while the vessel was still under construction. ''Hurricane'' was the first clipper built by Smith, who had \"no previous experiences in building fast sizeable ships\";<ref name=fairburn_p2128/> she was also by far the largest ship to come from Smith{{'}}s Hoboken shipyard.{{efn|See the shipbuilding record section in the [[Isaac C. Smith]] article.}} Her owners, C. W. & A. Thomas,{{efn|The firm is misnamed C. W. & '''H'''. Thomas in ''American Lloyds'', an error consequently repeated by some later sources.}} a firm involved mainly in the importation of French [[textile]]s to the United States, are not known to have owned any other notable clippers.<ref name=fairburn_p2128/>\n\n''Hurricane'' was built of [[live oak]], with [[white oak]] [[keel]], [[kelson]] and frame and \"live oak and [[Robinia|locust]] top\";<ref name=nytimes_11nov1851>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= New Clipper Ship 'Hurricane' |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/18157552/clipper_hurricane_launch_1851/ |work= The New York Times |date= 1851-11-11 |page= 1 }}</ref> her timbers were \"thoroughly salted on the stocks.\"<ref name=nytimes_11nov1851/> ''Hurricane''{{'}}s fastenings were of copper and iron, square bolted throughout, and she was said to be an exceptionally heavily timbered and strongly built vessel.<ref name=nytimes_11nov1851/> She had an overall length of {{convert|230|ft}}, {{convert|215|ft}} on deck and {{convert|206|ft}} keel, with a [[beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|40|ft}}, [[hold (ship)|hold]] depth of {{convert|22|ft}} and [[draft (hull)|draft]] of {{convert|20|ft}}.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277/><ref name=nytimes_11nov1851/><ref name=fairburn_p2129/> She had two decks, and was fitted with passenger accommodations in addition to her cargo capacity. Her registered tonnage was 1608 [[tons burthen]].<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277/><ref name=fairburn_p2128/><ref name=nytimes_11nov1851/> \n\nAccording to some authorities, ''Hurricane'' was \"the sharpest sailing ship ever constructed by any builder\"<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277/><ref name=nytimes_11nov1851/><ref name=fairburn_p2129>Fairburn 1945&ndash;55. '''III'''. p. [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015021129070?urlappend=%3Bseq=561 2129].</ref>&mdash;that is, the most extreme clipper<ref name=knoblock2014_p37>Knoblock 2014. p. 37.</ref>&mdash;though her model fore and aft is nonetheless said to have avoided [[concave]] lines.<ref name=nytimes_11nov1851/> She had a deadrise of {{convert|40|in|cm}}<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277/> typical of the early extreme clippers. It was said that no other vessel had lines below water \"sweeter than those of the ''Hurricane'', for, in her, resistance to driving through water was reduced to a minimum.\"<ref name=fairburn_p2129/> The disadvantage of such sharp lines was a corresponding reduction in cargo capacity, which ran the risk of making the extreme clippers unprofitable during periods of low freight rates.<ref name=fairburn_pp2128-29>Fairburn 1945&ndash;55. '''III'''. pp. [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015021129070?urlappend=%3Bseq=560 2128&ndash;29].</ref> At the time of ''Hurricane''{{'}}s debut, however, this was not a concern as rates were still at unprecedented highs due to the [[California Gold Rush]], then in full swing.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277>Howe and Matthews 1926. '''I'''. p. [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015020225044?urlappend=%3Bseq=347 277].</ref>\n\n''Hurricane'' had a \"graceful\" rising [[Bow (ship)|bow]] and rounded [[stern]], with a heavy brass rail running around the [[poop deck]].<ref name=nytimes_11nov1851/> The bow was decorated with a \"very handsome\" eagle{{'}}s head, which had a ribbon flowing from its mouth upon which was inscribed the ship{{'}}s name in gilt letters, the whole creating \"a very novel appearance.\"<ref name=nytimes_11nov1851/>{{efn|Howe and Matthews state that the eagle{{'}}s head and ribbon decorations were located on the ship{{'}}s stern rather than bow,<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277/> in contradiction of contemporaneous newspaper accounts.}} ''Hurricane'' was loftily sparred and fitted with rolling topsails, with her name emblazoned across the lower part of the foretopsail in large black lettering<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277/> \"that could be read much further than any signals and looked very smart and shipshape.\"<ref name=clark1910_p163/> Overall, she was described as a \"truly beautiful ship\".<ref name=nytimes_11nov1851/> \n\n=== Launch ===\n\n''Hurricane'' was launched with all her standing [[spar (sailing)|spars]]<ref name=nytimes_11nov1851/> on the morning of 25 October 1851,<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277/> witnessed by an \"immense concourse\" of spectators. After the launch, the vessel \"remained afloat several days with nearly all her [[yard (sailing)|yards]] aloft, without a pound of [[ballast]] in her\", a tribute to her stability.<ref name=nytimes_11nov1851/>\n\n''Hurricane''{{'}}s launch was widely reported across the country, with some seeing the event not merely as the launch of an exceptional ship, but as a symbol of the growing confidence of the young Republic. A reporter from a [[Washington, D.C.]], periodical, after noting how the vessel \"sparred enormously, looms up prodigiously ... [and] overtops and belittles everything afloat lying near\"<ref name=therepublic_5nov1851>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= New York Correspondence |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/18582739/hurricane_clipper_grandeur/ |work= The Republic |location= Washington, D.C. |date= 1851-11-05 |page= 2}}</ref> was given to further reflect that \"The tendency in every thing with us is toward magnificence of dimensions ... the day of cheap things is past altogether. Grandeur, speed and magnificence are the ruling ideas in the American mind.\"<ref name=therepublic_5nov1851/> Another journalist from [[North Carolina]] was sufficiently moved by news of the launch to declare: \"We are a great people and [[Nicknames of New York City|Gotham]] is magnificent.\"<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Big Ships |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19312121/hurricane_1851_clipper_launch_means_a/ |work= Weekly Commercial |location= Wilmington, NC |date= 1851-11-14 |page= 2 }}</ref> Others confined their admiration to the ship itself. A reporter writing some weeks after the launch described the ship \"with all her sails and colors flying\" as \"one of the most cheering nautical sights ever shown in this region\".<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Kossuth in New York |url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19312167/hurricane_1851_clipper_a_cheering/ |work= The Raleigh Register |location= Raleigh, NC |date= 1851-12-13 |page= 2 }}</ref>\n\n=== Command ===\n\n''Hurricane''{{'}}s first master, who would command the vessel for the first six years of her service, was Captain Samuel Very Jr., son of John Crowninshield Very, a [[Salem, Massachusetts|Salem]] mariner,<ref name=fairburn_p2128/> and father of future [[United States Navy]] [[Rear Admiral]] Samuel W. Very.<ref name=clark1910_p163>Clark 1910. p. [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/hvd.hntl1d?urlappend=%3Bseq=215 163].</ref> Captain Very Jr. would prove to be \"a capable master and good navigator\",<ref name=fairburn_p2128/> under whose command ''Hurricane'' would set or equal a number of point-to-point or port-to-port records.{{efn|See service history section below.}}\n\n== Service history ==\n=== Very captaincy, 1851&ndash;57 === \n[[ File:Hurricane (1851 clipper) maiden voyage advertisement.jpg | thumb | Advertisement for ''Hurricane''{{'}}s maiden voyage ]] \nPrior to ''Hurricane''{{'}}s launch, a voyage to [[China]] via [[San Francisco]], [[California]], had already been organized for the vessel, but some weeks were to pass after launch before the ship was ready to sail. ''Hurricane'' eventually departed New York for San Francisco on her maiden voyage on 17 December 1851, with Captain Samuel Very Jr. in command.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277/>\n\nSixteen days out from New York, ''Hurricane''{{'}}s fore and main topmasts and mizzen topgallant mast were lost in a [[white squall]], but despite the mishap, the ship crossed the equator in good time and arrived at [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]], on 28 January 1852, where she put in for repairs.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277/><ref name=fairburn_pp2129-30>Fairburn 1945&ndash;55. '''III'''. pp. [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015021129070?urlappend=%3Bseq=561 2129&ndash;2130].</ref> These were effected in the space of 12 days<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277/>&mdash;then considered a remarkably short time for this port<ref name=fairburn_p2130>Fairburn 1945&ndash;55. '''III'''. p. [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015021129070?urlappend=%3Bseq=562 2130].</ref>&mdash;and the ship resumed her journey 9 February,<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277/><ref name=fairburn_p2130/> reaching the [[Pacific Ocean]] 24 days later and enjoying a \"fine run\"<ref name=howe&matthews_I_pp277-78>Howe and Matthews 1926. '''I'''. pp. [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015020225044?urlappend=%3Bseq=347 277&ndash;78].</ref> of 18 days to the equator, thereafter completing the final leg to San Francisco in 24 days, where she arrrived 15 April.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_pp277-78/> ''Hurricane''{{'}}s time on her first New York&ndash;to&ndash;San Francisco voyage was 120 days overall including the 12-day stopover at Rio, her net sailing days thus totalling just 108, while her run of 66 days from Rio to San Francisco<ref name=fairburn_p2130/> has been described as \"only once beaten and only twice equalled\"<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p278/> in the history of merchant sail.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p278>Howe and Matthews 1926. '''I'''. p. [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015020225044?urlappend=%3Bseq=348 278].</ref> ''Hurricane'' is also said to have travelled 400 nautical miles in a single day on the passage from Rio, at times reaching speeds of up to 18 knots,<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277/><ref name=fairburn_p2130/> and while this claim has been queried, according to [[naval architect]] [[William Armstrong Fairburn|William Fairburn]] the vessel was \"fully capable\"<ref name=fairburn_p2130/> of achieving such speeds in the right conditions.<ref name=fairburn_p2130/> \n\nAfter making port at San Francisco, ''Hurricane'' continued on her scheduled trip to China, returning to San Francisco from [[Pazhou|Whampoa]] 20 October after a 43-day transpacific crossing.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p278/> The ship then made a second transpacific crossing, this time to [[Hong Kong]], in a time of 44 days.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p278/> Loading again at Whampoa, the vessel cleared port 12 February 1853 for her home port of New York, arriving at her destination 18 May after a passage of 94 1/2 days.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p278/>\n\n''Hurricane'' departed on her second New York&ndash;to&ndash;San Francisco voyage on 9 August 1853, but on this trip was beset by much calm weather as well as losing her [[jibboom]] and foretopgallant mast in the vicinity of [[Cape Horn]], before arriving at San Francisco after a 123-day passage.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p278/> In spite of the adverse conditions encountered, ''Hurricane''{{'}}s run of 25 days from [[Sandy Hook]] to the equator on the outset of this voyage is said to have \"never been bettered and seldom equalled for August departures.\"<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p278/> ''Hurricane'' then returned to New York in ballast, clearing San Francisco 31 December and arriving at her destination in early April after a passage of 96 days.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p278/>\n[[ File:Flyingcloudclipper2.jpg | thumb | left | The clipper [[Flying Cloud (clipper)|''Flying Cloud'']]]] \n''Hurricane''{{'}}s third and fastest New York&ndash;to&ndash;San Francisco voyage began on 26 May 1854. After just 85 days in transit, the ship was only 1,040 miles from San Francisco and within striking distance of [[Flying Cloud (clipper)|''Flying Cloud'']]{{'}}s all-time record passage of 89 days, but at this point was beset by light winds and calms,<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p278/> taking another two weeks to cover the remaining distance and eventually logging a nonetheless outstanding passage of 100 days (99 days 16 hours pilot to pilot).<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p279>Howe and Matthews 1926. '''I'''. p. [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015020225044?urlappend=%3Bseq=349 279].</ref><ref name=fairburn_p2130/> Captain Very was particularly proud of his ship{{'}}s performance through the challenging region of [[the tropics]] on this voyage, noting that the vessel averaged more than {{convert|8|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} through both the Atlantic and Pacific legs, and recording in his log the conviction that \"these two portions of our passage have rarely, if ever, been equalled\"<ref name=fairburn_p2130/>&mdash;passages later verified by Cutler as all-time records.<ref name=cutler1952_p109>Cutler 1952. p. 109.</ref> Fairburn has additionally noted ''Hurricane''{{'}}s \"unusually uniform\"<ref name=fairburn_p2131>Fairburn 1945&ndash;55. '''III'''. p. [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015021129070?urlappend=%3Bseq=563 2131].</ref> speeds under varying conditions on this passage,<ref name=fairburn_p2131/> and argued that with a little more good fortune, the vessel could well have set considerably faster times throughout her career.<ref name=fairburn_p2129/>\n\nAfter arriving at San Francisco, ''Hurricane'' made a 40-day passage to Hong Kong, departing 21 September and arriving 1 November, before continuing on to [[Calcutta]], [[India]], on a leg which included a very fast passage of 6 1/2 days from Hong Kong to [[Singapore]] at an average speed of just under {{convert|10|kn|mph km/h}}.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p279/><ref name=fairburn_p2132>Fairburn 1945&ndash;55. '''III'''. p. [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015021129070?urlappend=%3Bseq=564 2132].</ref> Clearing Calcutta 3 February 1855, the ship made a 100-day passage around the [[Cape of Good Hope]] to [[London]], [[England]].<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p279/> From London, the vessel returned to Calcutta, on this occasion making the run from [[The Needles]] to the mouth of the [[Hooghly River]] in 82 1/4 days,<ref name=fairburn_p2132/> setting a record \"not beaten or equalled for many years thereafter.\"<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p279/> Leaving Calcutta 10 January 1856, the ship returned to [[Falmouth, Cornwall|Falmouth]], England, in the fast time of 83 days (79 sailing days)<ref name=fairburn_p2132/> before departing from London for Hong Kong, where she arrived 5 October 1856.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p279/> \n\nAfter almost four months at Hong Kong, ''Hurricane'' sailed for San Francisco 20 January 1857, arriving 13 March.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p279/> At this point, an unsuccessful attempt was made to sell the vessel. ''Hurricane'' eventually sailed from San Francisco 16 June for New York, arriving 28 September 1857 after a 104-day passage.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p279/> This was to be the last voyage of ''Hurricane'' under the command of Captain Very,<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p277/><ref name=fairburn_p2128/> whose family returned to New York with him on this passage.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Postscript |url= http://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2010/New%20York%20NY%20Evening%20Post/New%20York%20NY%20Evening%20Post%201857%20Grayscale/New%20York%20NY%20Evening%20Post%201857%20Grayscale%20-%200932.pdf |work= The Evening Post |location= New York |date= 1857-09-29 |page= 3}}</ref>\n\n=== Later history ===\n[[ File:Hurricane (1851 clipper) last voyage to San Francisco advert.jpg | thumb | Advertisement for ''Hurricane''{{'}}s last New York to San Francisco voyage, 1858 ]] \nAfter returning to New York in September 1857, ''Hurricane'' was laid up with no work until the end of 1858 due to low freight rates caused in part by [[Panic of 1857|an economic depression]] in the United States.<ref name=fairburn_p2128/><ref name=howe&matthews_I_p279/> While other vessels could continue to operate profitably in such conditions, extreme clippers like ''Hurricane'', with their high operating costs and relatively light tonnages, could not.<ref name=fairburn_p2128/><ref name=howe&matthews_I_p279/> Toward the end of 1858, ''Hurricane'' was again placed in commission&mdash;reportedly in hopes of finding a buyer&mdash;and on 8 January 1859, departed for the fourth and final time for San Francisco, Captain Ichabod Sherman in command.<ref name=fairburn_p2128/><ref name=howe&matthews_I_p279/><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Ocean Steamers, &c. |url= http://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%206/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201858%20Oct%20-%20Dec%20Grayscale/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201858%20Oct%20-%20Dec%20Grayscale%20-%200519.pdf |work= New-York Daily Tribune |date= 1858-12-15 |page= 3 }}</ref> On this voyage, ''Hurricane'' reportedly experienced much adverse weather, arriving at San Francisco 30 May after an unexceptional 143-day passage.<ref name=fairburn_p2128/><ref name=howe&matthews_I_p280>Howe and Matthews 1926. '''I'''. p. [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015020225044?urlappend=%3Bseq=350 280].</ref>\n\nFrom San Francisco, ''Hurricane'' sailed for Singapore 3 September, arriving 7 November.<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p280/> There, she was sold in 1860 for US$30,000 ({{inflation|US|30,000|1859|fmt=eq|cursign=US$}}) and went under the [[United Kingdom|British]] flag.<ref name=fairburn_p2128/><ref name=howe&matthews_I_p280/> Renamed ''Shaw-Allum'',<ref name=howe&matthews_I_p280/> little is known about the vessel{{'}}s subsequent career.<ref name=fairburn_p2128/> Her last known mention in shipping registers was in 1876.<ref name=fairburn_p2128/><ref name=howe&matthews_I_p280/>\n\n== Footnotes == \n{{notelist}}\n\n== References == \n{{Reflist|30em}} \n=== Bibliography ===\n\n* {{cite book |last= Clark |first= Arthur Hamilton |date= 1910 |title= The Clipper Ship Era: An Epitome of Famous American and British Clipper Ships, Their Owners, Builders, Commanders, and Crews 1843&ndash;1869 |location= New York |publisher= G. P. Putnam{{'}}s Sons |page= [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/hvd.hntl1d?urlappend=%3Bseq=215 163] }} \n* {{cite book |last= Fairburn |first= William Armstrong |date= 1945\u201355 |title= Merchant Sail |volume= III |location= Center Lovell, Maine |publisher= Fairburn Marine Educational Foundation, Inc. |pages= [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015021129070?urlappend=%3Bseq=560 2128\u201332] |author-link= }} \n* {{cite book |last= Howe |first= Octavius T. |last2= Matthews |first2= Frederick C. |date= 1926 |title= American Clipper Ships 1833\u20131858 |volume= I |location= Salem, Massachusetts |publisher= Marine Research Society |pages= [https://hdl.handle.net/2027/mdp.39015020225044?urlappend=%3Bseq=347 277\u201380] }}\n* {{cite book |last= Knoblock |first= Glenn A. |author-link= |date= 2014 |title= The American Clipper Ship, 1845\u20141920 |location= Jefferson, NC |publisher= McFarland & Company |page= 37 |isbn= 9780786471126 }} \n[[Category:1851 ships]] \n[[Category:Ships built by Isaac C. Smith| ]] \n[[Category:Clipper ships built in New Jersey| 