{"title_page": "1978 Philippine parliamentary election", "text_new": "{{short description|Election in the Philippines in 1978}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 1978 Philippine parliamentary election\n| country = Philippines\n| flag_year = 1936\n| type = parliamentary\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 1969 Philippine House of Representatives elections\n| previous_year = 1969\n| next_election = 1984 Philippine parliamentary election\n| next_year = 1984\n| election_date = April 7 and 27, 1978\n| seats_for_election = 179 (of the 189) seats in the [[Interim Batasang Pambansa]]\n| majority_seats=95\n| image1 =[[File:Ferdinand Marcos.JPEG|100px]]\n| leader1 = [[Ferdinand Marcos]]\n| party1 = Kilusang Bagong Lipunan\n| leaders_seat1 = none\n| last_election1 = ''new party''\n| seats1 = 150\n| seat_change1 = {{increase}} 150\n| popular_vote1=155,866,553\n| percentage1=74.97%\n\n| image2 = <div style=\"width:100px;\"><span style=\"line-height:100px; vertical-align:center; text-align:center; color:{{Pusyon Bisaya/meta/color}}; font-size:30px;\">'''PB'''</span></div>\n| leader2 = [[Hilario Davide, Jr.]]\n| party2 = Pusyon Bisaya\n| leaders_seat2 = [[Central Visayas|Region VII]]\n| last_election2 = ''new party''\n| seats2 = 13\n| seat_change2 = {{increase}} 13\n| popular_vote2=9,495,416\n| percentage2=4.57%\n\n| image3 = <div style=\"width:100px;\"><span style=\"line-height:100px; vertical-align:center; text-align:center; color:{{Mindanao Alliance/meta/color}}; font-size:30px;\">'''MA'''</span></div>\n| leader3 = Reuben Canoy\n| party3 = Mindanao Alliance\n| leaders_seat3 = [[Northern Mindanao|Region X]]\n| last_election3 = ''new party''\n| seats3 = 1\n| seat_change3 = {{increase}} 1\n| popular_vote3=6,685,224\n| percentage3=3.22%\n\n| image4 = <div style=\"width:100px;\"><span style=\"line-height:100px; vertical-align:center; text-align:center; color:{{Independent politician/meta/color}}; font-size:30px;\">'''KB'''</span></div>\n| leader4 = Ernesto Roldan\n| party4 = [[Independent politician|Independent]] / [[Konsensiya ng Bayan]]{{ref|a|A}}\n| color4 =DDDDDD\n| leaders_seat4 = [[Central Mindanao|Region XII]]\n| last_election4 = ''new party''\n| seats4 = 1\n| seat_change4 = {{increase}} 1\n| popular_vote4=7,633,851\n| percentage4=3.67%\n\n| image5 = [[File:Ninoy Aquino 3.jpg|100px]]\n| leader5 = [[Benigno Aquino, Jr.]]\n| party5 = Lakas ng Bayan\n| leaders_seat5 = [[Metro Manila|Region IV-A]] ''(lost)''\n| last_election5 = ''new party''\n| seats5 = 0\n| seat_change5 = {{steady}}\n| popular_vote5=21,541,600\n| percentage5=10.36%\n\n| title = [[Prime Minister of the Philippines|Prime Minister]]\n| posttitle = [[Prime Minister of the Philippines|Prime Minister]]-designate\n| after_election  = [[Ferdinand Marcos]]\n| after_party = Kilusang Bagong Lipunan\n}}\n{{Politics of Philippines}}\nA '''parliamentary election''' was held in the [[Philippines]] on April 7, 1978 for the election of the 165 regional representatives to the [[Interim Batasang Pambansa]] (the nation's first parliament). The elections were participated in by the leading opposition party, the [[Lakas ng Bayan]] (LABAN), which had twenty-one candidates for the Metro Manila area while the leading candidate was the jailed opposition leader [[Benigno Aquino, Jr.|Ninoy Aquino]], and the Marcos regime's party known as the [[Kilusang Bagong Lipunan]] (KBL), which was led by the then-First Lady [[Imelda Marcos]]. Ninoy was allowed to run by his fellow partymates under the [[Liberal Party (Philippines)|Liberal Party]], who boycotted the election and was not allowed to campaign, and so his family campaigned for him. The night before the election on April 6, 1978, a noise barrage was organized by the supporters of (LABAN) which occurred up to dawn.\n\nThese elections were followed by the [[1978 Philippine parliamentary sectoral election|sectoral election]] on April 27, which elected additional 14 representatives. Another 10 representatives were appointed, bringing up the total number of representatives to 189.\n\n== Background ==\nThe Philippines had been under [[martial law]] since 1972, with incumbent president [[Ferdinand Marcos]] ruling by decree. Prior to this, the [[Constitution of the Philippines]] was being drafted by the [[1971 Philippine Constitutional Convention|Constitutional Convention]], whose delegates were [[1970 Philippine Constitutional Convention election|elected in 1970]]. The Constitutional Convention approved the final draft of the constitution, which consisted of the abolition of the Philippine Congress and its replacement with an interim National Assembly consisting of the President, the Vice-President, the President of the Constitutional Convention, and members of the Senate and the House of Representatives in November 1972 and was [[1973 Philippine constitutional plebiscite|later ratified]] on January 17, 1973 through so-called \"citizens' assemblies\". The Constitution was amended twice, on [[1973 Philippine Martial Law referendum|July 27\u201328, 1973]] and [[1975 Philippine executive and legislative powers referendum|February 27\u201328, 1975]]. The Constitution was amended once again on [[1976 Philippine constitutional plebiscite|October 16\u201317, 1976]] with the passage of \"Amendment No. 6\", which changed the name of the Interim National Assembly into the \"Interim Batasang Pambansa\", more commonly as the \"Batasan\".\n\n== Campaign ==\n=== Lakas ng Bayan ===\n{{Main|Lakas ng Bayan}}\nIn 1978, from his prison cell, Aquino was allowed to take part in the elections. Although his friends, former Senators [[Gerardo Roxas|Gerry Roxas]] and [[Jovito Salonga]], preferred to boycott the elections, Aquino urged his supporters to field 21 candidates in [[Metro Manila]]. Thus, his political party, dubbed ''[[Lakas ng Bayan]]'' (\"People's Power\"), was born. The party's acronym was \"LABAN\" (\"fight\" in [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]]). He was entitled to one television interview on [[People's Television Network|GTV]]'s ''Face the Nation'' (hosted by [[Ronnie Nathanielsz]]), and proved to a startled and impressed populace that imprisonment had neither dulled his rapier-like tongue nor dampened his fighting spirit. Foreign correspondents and diplomats asked what would happen to the LABAN ticket. People agreed with him that his party would win overwhelmingly in an honest election. On April 6, 1978, supporters of the [[Lakas ng Bayan]] (LABAN), the opposition party headed by former Senator [[Benigno Aquino, Jr.]] who was still in jail and twenty other candidates contesting the Region IV-A (Metro Manila) seats, came out in protest by asking bystanders and cars to make noise in support the opposition.\n\n=== Kilusang Bagong Lipunan ===\nPresident Marcos created the [[Kilusang Bagong Lipunan]] (New Society Movement) as his political vehicle for the elections.\n\n== Results ==\nThe top bar represents seats won, while the bottom bar represents the proportion of votes received.\n{| width=70% border=0 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0\n|-\n|+ \u2193\n|-align=center\n|style=\"border:1px solid #000000;\" width=87.30%|'''District'''\n|style=\"border:1px solid #000000;\" width=12.70%|'''Other'''\n|-\n|\n{|width=100% style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-style=\"font-weight:bold; font-size:90%;\"\n|width=90.90% bgcolor={{Kilusang Bagong Lipunan/meta/color}}|<span style=\"color:white;\">150</span>\n|width=7.88% bgcolor={{Pusyon Bisaya/meta/color}}|<span style=\"color:white;\">13</span>\n|width=0.61% bgcolor={{Mindanao Alliance/meta/color}}|<span style=\"color:white;\">1</span>\n|width=0.61% bgcolor={{Independent politician/meta/color}}|1\n|}\n|\n{|width=100% style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-style=\"font-weight:bold; font-size:90%;\"\n|width=58.33% bgcolor=#36454F|<span style=\"color:white;\">14</span>\n|width=41.67% bgcolor=gray|<span style=\"color:white;\">10</span>\n|}\n|-\n|\n{|width=100% style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-style=\"font-weight:bold; font-size:90%;\"\n|width=74.97% bgcolor={{Kilusang Bagon